This wonderful house, replete with it's rich architectural details, appears to be <a href="http://maps.google.com/maps?cbp=12,185.15,,0,-6.86&amp;cbll=-27.556601,151.962423&amp;layer=c&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;ll=-27.55663,151.962612&amp;spn=0.004404,0.006877&amp;z=17&amp;panoid=TT36O2Dtj1hSUC297nmDWg" rel="nofollow">standing today</a>.

&quot;Whyembah was built c1896 for John Rosser, a commercial traveller with the Brisbane firm of Thurlow and Co. Whyembah originally stood on approximately 1r 29p of land, adjacent to the Toowoomba Botanic Gardens [now known as Queens Park Gardens] in Campbell Street. Rosser was a keen lawn bowler, and the grounds of Whyembah included a bowling green at one time.&quot;

A more detailed history can be found at <i><a href="http://www.epa.qld.gov.au/chims/placeDetail.html?siteId=15616" rel="nofollow">Queensland Heritage Register</a>.</i>
